<Doc
  title="Manifesto — Chips and the agentic web"
  description="The right unit of identity for AI commerce is not the session, the device, or the IP. It's the durable link between a person, their agent, and the brands they've already said yes to."
  pageLabel="MANIFESTO"
  eyebrow="THE THESIS · UNABRIDGED"
  heading={`The right unit of <em>identity</em><br/>for AI commerce<span class="dot">.</span>`}
  lede="The agentic web is not the next layer of the page web. It's a different artifact — a network of conversations between agents about people. The protocol it needs is not a cookie or an OAuth scope. It's a durable, consented, cross-enterprise context bridge with a learning layer beneath."
>
  <div class="prose">
    <p class="big-quote">
      <em>"The right unit of identity for AI commerce is not the session, the device, or the IP. It's the
      durable link between a person, their agent, and the brands they've already said yes to."</em>
    </p>

    <h2>The page web was wired for surveillance.</h2>
    <p>
      Browser cookies are used against you. Every site you visit drops a beacon, every ad network triangulates
      across them, and the consumer pays in attention and privacy for a system that pretends to serve them.
      The page web's identity layer is adversarial by construction — the consumer is the product, the
      advertiser is the customer, the publisher is the conduit.
    </p>

    <h2>The agentic web is a different artifact.</h2>
    <p>
      A consumer agent talks to an enterprise agent on the consumer's behalf. The enterprise agent runs the
      enterprise's policy and observes the conversation. The consumer never visits a page; the page is dead.
      The session is dead. The cookie is dead. <em>What's alive is the conversation, and the question is who
      owns the context that flows between those conversations.</em>
    </p>

    <Callout variant="quote">
      <p>
        Browser cookies are used <strong>against</strong> you.<br/>
        Chips cookies are used <strong>for</strong> you.
      </p>
    </Callout>

    <h2>Chips closes the loop.</h2>
    <p>
      <em>Enterprises</em> get attribution and personalization for agent traffic — richer than any cookie,
      durable across devices. <em>Consumers</em> get a context layer that travels with their agent rather
      than locking them to one storefront. <em>Both parties opt in transparently, and the policy on what
      enterprises can do with that data is enforced in the protocol, not in a privacy statement.</em>
    </p>

    <h2>The standard already exists.</h2>
    <p>
      A2A — Agent-to-Agent protocol, governed by the Linux Foundation, with 150+ enterprise deployments in
      its first year — already prescribes how a consumer agent authenticates to an enterprise agent. It uses
      OIDC delegated user auth. It carries email and sub claims. <em>Chips is built directly on this
      standard.</em> The consumer agent doesn't need a Chips integration. The consumer doesn't need a
      Chips account.
    </p>
    <p>
      What Chips adds is the <em>cross-enterprise context bridge</em> — the consent-mediated mechanism that
      lets one enterprise's agent ask another enterprise's agent for context the consumer has authorized to
      share — and the <em>privacy-preserving network learning layer</em> beneath, where every conversation
      structures into events that compound into priors no single enterprise or hyperscaler can credibly
      replicate.
    </p>

    <h2>The moat is twofold.</h2>
    <p>
      <em>The bridge is the moat people see.</em> Legible to enterprises within minutes: <em>"we can answer
      questions across the network for your customer with their permission."</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Network learning is the moat that compounds.</em> Five loops at two levels — Level A locally at the
      enterprise, Level B aggregated across the network under differential privacy. The pattern is closer to
      a Bloomberg Terminal than to a feature: it takes six months to communicate the value, and it locks in
      once it's understood.
    </p>

    <h2>Hyperscalers cannot follow.</h2>
    <p>
      Bedrock and Foundry can host enterprise agents. They cannot credibly aggregate cross-enterprise signal,
      because their commercial relationships compete with the enterprises they'd aggregate from. Consumer
      agents can route consumers, but they cannot run the enterprise side. <em>Chips is the neutral
      cross-enterprise broker whose commercial relationship is with enterprises, optionally with consumer
      agents as a partnership layer, and never with the consumer directly.</em>
    </p>

    <h2>And the first cohort is closing.</h2>
    <p>
      Phase 1 is white-glove onboarding for ten outdoor &amp; athletic apparel enterprises. Phase 2 is
      self-serve Studio + the first Level B prior release for the category. <em>Phase 3 is network density
      compounding across categories.</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      Apply early. The launch cohort shapes the scope vocabulary, the event taxonomy, and the priors every
      subsequent enterprise inherits.
    </p>

    <div class="end-ctas">
